00:56:51.977 --> 00:56:53.060
That's an important thing.

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:56.170
We didn't pick up a cabbage,
and find the internet.

00:56:58.990 --> 00:57:01.240
DAVID: In fact maybe my
question ought to be for Vint.

00:57:01.240 --> 00:57:02.951
Would the internet
have been built?

00:57:02.951 --> 00:57:04.950
VINT CERF: Well there
would have been something.

00:57:04.950 --> 00:57:05.824
And I agree with you.

00:57:05.824 --> 00:57:10.490
We had a little discussion
before this, this afternoon.

00:57:10.490 --> 00:57:13.350
A lot of things happened because
it's now possible for them

00:57:13.350 --> 00:57:14.240
to happen.

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:17.080
There was a lot going
on in networking.

00:57:17.080 --> 00:57:19.790
Internet happened to
have been the design that

00:57:19.790 --> 00:57:21.280
was most successful.

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:23.590
But there were several other
networking technologies

00:57:23.590 --> 00:57:24.500
at the time.

00:57:24.500 --> 00:57:28.320
There were some
proprietary, some like X.25

00:57:28.320 --> 00:57:30.720
was a global thing.

00:57:30.720 --> 00:57:33.160
The OSI structure, it
was another proposal.

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:35.860
So yes, I agree with you that
something would have happened,

00:57:35.860 --> 00:57:37.030
because it was possible.

00:57:37.030 --> 00:57:39.260
And many people were
thinking about it,

00:57:39.260 --> 00:57:41.070
and trying experiments.

00:57:41.070 --> 00:57:42.430
So I agree with that.

00:57:42.430 --> 00:57:45.610
But I'm glad that the one
that I worked on came out OK.

00:57:45.610 --> 00:57:46.400
DAVID: Me too.

00:57:46.400 --> 00:57:47.580
Thank you.

00:57:47.580 --> 00:57:50.460
ERIC WEINER: I guess I don't
see them as that different.

00:57:50.460 --> 00:57:53.460
I think creativity
is creativity,

00:57:53.460 --> 00:57:56.100
but there are some
differences, you're right.

00:57:56.100 --> 00:57:57.900
An art historian
in Florence told me

00:57:57.900 --> 00:57:59.830
that, what made the
David the David,

00:57:59.830 --> 00:58:03.140
is that once it was created,
people knew it was the best,

00:58:03.140 --> 00:58:05.730
and knew there would
not be an upgrade.

00:58:05.730 --> 00:58:08.820
A David 2.0, right?

00:58:08.820 --> 00:58:11.940
A piece of art like that,
renders any idea of improvement

00:58:11.940 --> 00:58:13.450
silly, really.

00:58:13.450 --> 00:58:15.000
And of course,
science and technology

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:17.270
is always being improved upon.

00:58:17.270 --> 00:58:20.440
I mean, Steve Jobs,
shortly before his death,

00:58:20.440 --> 00:58:24.590
was asked about the connection
between Renaissance Florence

00:58:24.590 --> 00:58:25.396
and Silicon Valley.

00:58:25.396 --> 00:58:27.020
And he, I think,
rightfully pointed out

00:58:27.020 --> 00:58:30.240
one of the differences is that
the artists of Renaissance

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:32.780
Florence were creating
something for all time,

00:58:32.780 --> 00:58:35.220
to last forever,
through the ages.

00:58:35.220 --> 00:58:37.787
And in Silicon Valley
they're creating something--

00:58:37.787 --> 00:58:39.870
VINT CERF: That lasts six
months, if you're lucky.

00:58:39.870 --> 00:58:41.960
ERIC WEINER: Thank you
for completing the line.

00:58:41.960 --> 00:58:43.060
You're right.

00:58:43.060 --> 00:58:46.150
And that is the difference.

00:58:46.150 --> 00:58:48.400
There are differences,
but I just

00:58:48.400 --> 00:58:50.630
have a feeling that the
creative scientist, and that

00:58:50.630 --> 00:58:54.150
is not an oxymoron, has more in
common with a creative artist

00:58:54.150 --> 00:58:57.200
than they think.

00:58:57.200 --> 00:59:01.180
But I try to put them
under an umbrella,

00:59:01.180 --> 00:59:03.950
because we consider them genius.

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:07.360
We consider Mozart a genius, and
we consider Einstein a genius.

00:59:07.360 --> 00:59:09.080
And we don't modify either one.

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:12.020
We don't say that Einstein
was a scientific genius.

00:59:12.020 --> 00:59:13.790
And that Mozart was
a musical genius.

00:59:13.790 --> 00:59:16.190
We tend to just use
the word genius, so

00:59:16.190 --> 00:59:19.800
that they transcend
their excellence,

00:59:19.800 --> 00:59:26.290
and their je ne sais quoi,
got the French thing going,

00:59:26.290 --> 00:59:28.590
elevates them above
their particular field.

00:59:28.590 --> 00:59:31.900
And I do think that happens,
but it's a good point though.

00:59:31.900 --> 00:59:33.830
VINT CERF: OK, we have
a question back there.

00:59:33.830 --> 00:59:37.820
Do you have thoughts about
whether the physical attributes

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:39.660
of the place make a difference?

00:59:39.660 --> 00:59:41.450
ERIC WEINER: Yeah,
that's a good question.

00:59:41.450 --> 00:59:43.330
When I first got to
Athens, and you're

00:59:43.330 --> 00:59:47.040
struck by the sunshine in
Athens, 300 days a year

00:59:47.040 --> 00:59:47.550
of sunshine.

00:59:47.550 --> 00:59:51.650
And the light, which is very
striking, very severe, and it

00:59:51.650 --> 00:59:54.170
was a Greek painter,
Apollodorus,

00:59:54.170 --> 00:59:57.170
who first developed the
ability to use shadow to create

00:59:57.170 --> 00:59:58.480
the impression of depth.

00:59:58.480 --> 01:00:00.500
And that makes sense.

01:00:00.500 --> 01:00:02.740
And I thought, well,
is it the weather?

01:00:02.740 --> 01:00:04.300
Maybe that would be easy.

01:00:04.300 --> 01:00:07.500
But then you think about
Elizabeth London, no.

01:00:07.500 --> 01:00:10.240
That was not so sunny.

01:00:10.240 --> 01:00:14.120
I think the main thing
is, of the attributes,

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:16.670
is that they
provide a challenge.

01:00:16.670 --> 01:00:18.820
There are difficult places.

01:00:18.820 --> 01:00:20.450
Have you heard of the oil curse?

01:00:20.450 --> 01:00:21.830
And it goes by different names.

01:00:21.830 --> 01:00:25.690
It's basically the idea that
certain Persian Gulf nations

01:00:25.690 --> 01:00:28.030
are not particularly
innovative, because they just

01:00:28.030 --> 01:00:29.330
don't have to do be.

01:00:29.330 --> 01:00:33.060
That they're so awash in
oil, and even with oil prices

01:00:33.060 --> 01:00:35.520
where they are now,
and with natural gas,

01:00:35.520 --> 01:00:38.484
that they don't have
anything to push against.

01:00:38.484 --> 01:00:39.650
They don't have a challenge.

01:00:39.650 --> 01:00:41.270
So the one thing
that I think actually

01:00:41.270 --> 01:00:44.660
is important, is
to be challenged.

01:00:44.660 --> 01:00:46.450
Now in Athens, the
challenge was the land

01:00:46.450 --> 01:00:49.020
was crummy, and
didn't grow much.

01:00:49.020 --> 01:00:52.872
Florence was malarial,
and didn't have a seaport.

01:00:52.872 --> 01:00:54.340
Ah, Silicon Valley.

01:00:54.340 --> 01:00:55.840
What's the challenge?

01:00:55.840 --> 01:00:57.900
Too much Beauty No.

01:00:57.900 --> 01:01:00.240
I think it was the
isolation, separation,

01:01:00.240 --> 01:01:02.550
from the rest of the country.

01:01:02.550 --> 01:01:06.360
That really mattered
back in the early 1900s.

01:01:06.360 --> 01:01:09.054
They were able to
have a fresh start.

01:01:09.054 --> 01:01:10.470
They had a chip
on their shoulder.

01:01:10.470 --> 01:01:12.570
Not the microchip,
but the other kind.

01:01:12.570 --> 01:01:17.380
They wanted they wanted to
prove themselves, really.

01:01:17.380 --> 01:01:21.010
In an indirect way, yes, I think
the land itself plays a role.

01:01:21.010 --> 01:01:24.290
VINT CERF: Something interesting
about Silicon Valley.

01:01:24.290 --> 01:01:27.170
In the book you talk
about Fred Terman,

01:01:27.170 --> 01:01:28.890
and his father, Lewis Terman.

01:01:28.890 --> 01:01:31.600
Fred was provost of
Stanford University.

01:01:31.600 --> 01:01:33.770
But he was the
guy who recognized

01:01:33.770 --> 01:01:37.070
that the advances that were made
during the Second World War,

01:01:37.070 --> 01:01:40.740
were a consequence of government
investment in the Manhattan

01:01:40.740 --> 01:01:44.580
Project, in computers, and
things like that, radar.

01:01:44.580 --> 01:01:48.740
And he realized that there was
an opportunity for Stanford

01:01:48.740 --> 01:01:53.180
to continue that level of
creativity, and invention,

01:01:53.180 --> 01:01:56.640
and discovery, if they could get
continued government support.

01:01:56.640 --> 01:01:59.350
So he made the argument that
the government should continue

01:01:59.350 --> 01:02:01.510
to fund this kind
of research, and it

01:02:01.510 --> 01:02:06.370
enabled him to expand the
engineering and research

01:02:06.370 --> 01:02:08.410
department by a factor of three.

01:02:08.410 --> 01:02:09.920
Because basically,
instead of having

01:02:09.920 --> 01:02:14.220
to pay for the cost of the
professors out of tuition,

01:02:14.220 --> 01:02:17.114
he paid for 2/3 of their
cost out of research funds,

01:02:17.114 --> 01:02:19.780
which meant that they could have
three times as many professors,

01:02:19.780 --> 01:02:22.810
and still have one
third teaching load.

01:02:22.810 --> 01:02:26.930
And so part of the
Silicon Valley phenomenon,

01:02:26.930 --> 01:02:30.570
comes out of that
recognition and action.

01:02:30.570 --> 01:02:33.580
And after that,
he was the one who

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:35.650
counseled Hewlett
and Packard, as you

01:02:35.650 --> 01:02:38.530
wrote, to go start a
company, as opposed

01:02:38.530 --> 01:02:40.680
to going to work somewhere.

01:02:40.680 --> 01:02:46.400
And this idea of starting
companies starts with HP.

01:02:46.400 --> 01:02:48.550
And it continues to this day.

01:02:48.550 --> 01:02:50.790
And that whole
feedback loop, you

01:02:50.790 --> 01:02:53.210
mention in the book
about feedback loops,

01:02:53.210 --> 01:02:55.240
and how reinforcing they can be.

01:02:55.240 --> 01:02:58.150
I think Silicon Valley
discovered that feedback loop

01:02:58.150 --> 01:03:02.900
very early in the
game, in the 1950s.

01:03:02.900 --> 01:03:06.520
So let me get Mike, and then
we have one more over there.

01:03:06.520 --> 01:03:08.900
Oh, OK, so let's
take this one first.

01:03:08.900 --> 01:03:10.050
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:03:10.050 --> 01:03:11.110
Thank you for this topic.

01:03:11.110 --> 01:03:12.693
I think it's really
fascinating, and I

01:03:12.693 --> 01:03:15.200
was hoping you could talk a
little bit about what happened,

01:03:15.200 --> 01:03:17.180
or what you thought
about the societies,

01:03:17.180 --> 01:03:18.770
once the golden age ended.

01:03:18.770 --> 01:03:20.360
Was there anything in common?

01:03:20.360 --> 01:03:22.910
Do you think of anything
that's happened--

01:03:22.910 --> 01:03:24.880
these all happened in
different parts of time

01:03:24.880 --> 01:03:27.650
but taken together,
was there anything

01:03:27.650 --> 01:03:30.990
that China has in common
with Edinburgh, for example?

01:03:30.990 --> 01:03:33.010
ERIC WEINER: Do you mean
about why they ended?

01:03:33.010 --> 01:03:34.426
Or about what
happened afterwards?

01:03:34.426 --> 01:03:36.740
AUDIENCE: What happened to
the society, really, after?

01:03:36.740 --> 01:03:39.330
Did some of them
revert to a dark age?

01:03:39.330 --> 01:03:44.660
Do you still see some of
these factors for genius

01:03:44.660 --> 01:03:45.880
that could come back?

01:03:45.880 --> 01:03:47.630
ERIC WEINER: Yeah,
that's a good question.

01:03:47.630 --> 01:03:51.040
Obviously nothing
particularly good happens.

01:03:51.040 --> 01:03:55.770
But it's very interesting that
the Greeks, the Athenians, you

01:03:55.770 --> 01:03:58.130
can mark their
decline almost exactly

01:03:58.130 --> 01:04:00.577
with when they became foodies.

01:04:00.577 --> 01:04:02.410
Because, when they were
in their golden age,

01:04:02.410 --> 01:04:03.970
they were not into food at all.

01:04:03.970 --> 01:04:07.650
They had a very bland diet.

01:04:07.650 --> 01:04:10.060
Aristophanes, the
playwright and poet,

01:04:10.060 --> 01:04:14.170
attributed the keen Athenian
mind to their low calorie diet.

01:04:14.170 --> 01:04:17.550
And then they started
to eat gourmet food,

01:04:17.550 --> 01:04:21.560
and shop at the equivalent of
Williams and Sonoma, back then.

01:04:21.560 --> 01:04:23.430
No really, that
kind of decadence

01:04:23.430 --> 01:04:27.190
is, and getting back to someones
question about Silicon Valley,

01:04:27.190 --> 01:04:28.560
you see signs of that there.

01:04:28.560 --> 01:04:31.770
They tend to be one way
streets, for the most part.

01:04:31.770 --> 01:04:32.820
With a few exceptions.

01:04:32.820 --> 01:04:35.350
Being that once the
golden age happens,

01:04:35.350 --> 01:04:38.500
it takes a long, long time
for anything to come back.

01:04:38.500 --> 01:04:40.110
Vienna was a bit
of an exception,

01:04:40.110 --> 01:04:44.440
because you had
music in 1788, 1800,

01:04:44.440 --> 01:04:46.610
ending probably with Beethoven.

01:04:46.610 --> 01:04:48.730
And then 75, 100
years later, you

01:04:48.730 --> 01:04:51.860
had this huge explosion
with Freud and Gustav Klimt.

01:04:51.860 --> 01:04:53.430
So that was an exception.

01:04:53.430 --> 01:04:57.760
I think China can be an
exception to this one way rule,

01:04:57.760 --> 01:04:59.920
because the Chinese
view everything

01:04:59.920 --> 01:05:01.000
in a more cyclical way.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:03.540
They certainly view time
in a more cyclical way.

01:05:03.540 --> 01:05:05.350
We tend to view it as one way.

01:05:05.350 --> 01:05:09.070
That you get one
shot at everything.

01:05:09.070 --> 01:05:11.060
And I do address in
the book, this notion

01:05:11.060 --> 01:05:14.180
of what I call the golden
age hangover, which

01:05:14.180 --> 01:05:16.590
is, no seriously, in these
places that were great,

01:05:16.590 --> 01:05:18.260
and then where tourists
flock to today,

01:05:18.260 --> 01:05:22.810
to immerse themselves in,
and wallow in the greatness.

01:05:22.810 --> 01:05:24.120
Those are problems.

01:05:24.120 --> 01:05:25.880
You don't want to
be a young artist

01:05:25.880 --> 01:05:27.760
today, in Florence, Italy.

01:05:27.760 --> 01:05:29.520
I met with some of
them in a dinner party,

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:33.740
and the weight of
the past, they're

01:05:33.740 --> 01:05:36.870
visibly slumping in their
seat, their shoulders

01:05:36.870 --> 01:05:40.120
are slumping, because good
luck trying to do anything.

01:05:40.120 --> 01:05:42.280
And I meet with a Greek
philosopher today,

01:05:42.280 --> 01:05:45.760
and he's like, it's tough.

01:05:45.760 --> 01:05:47.580
I'm like, so what's
it like being

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:50.050
a Greek philosopher in 2015?

01:05:50.050 --> 01:05:51.925
And he said hungry.

01:05:51.925 --> 01:05:52.425
Very hungry.

01:05:56.380 --> 01:05:58.840
But less true for
Scotland, and some

01:05:58.840 --> 01:06:00.540
of the other places
that-- ironically,

01:06:00.540 --> 01:06:03.340
the places that are lesser
known on the world stage,

01:06:03.340 --> 01:06:06.190
and get fewer
tourists, they still

01:06:06.190 --> 01:06:09.250
have a bit more
creativity going on.

01:06:09.250 --> 01:06:10.580
VINT CERF: So here we go, Mike.

