ages, I was thinking,

01:08:51.370 --> 01:08:53.479
let's ignore cities
for just a moment,

01:08:53.479 --> 01:08:57.069
although in history, sometimes
the city and the culture

01:08:57.069 --> 01:08:59.020
were coterminous.

01:08:59.020 --> 01:09:01.850
Athens and Sparta, and so on.

01:09:01.850 --> 01:09:05.370
But let's imagine just
civilizations now, and forget

01:09:05.370 --> 01:09:07.510
about specific cities.

01:09:07.510 --> 01:09:12.630
Do you suppose, just based on
what you've already researched,

01:09:12.630 --> 01:09:16.180
are there similarities
between the cultures of each

01:09:16.180 --> 01:09:17.330
of those golden ages?

01:09:17.330 --> 01:09:19.390
So There's a golden
age in Persia,

01:09:19.390 --> 01:09:24.430
there's a golden age in China,
there's a golden age in Japan,

01:09:24.430 --> 01:09:30.790
is there anything about them
that you could correlate?

01:09:30.790 --> 01:09:33.109
Is there something
we can distill

01:09:33.109 --> 01:09:35.750
from looking at these
various golden ages

01:09:35.750 --> 01:09:38.760
that will tell us something
about how they start,

01:09:38.760 --> 01:09:41.450
and why they end?

01:09:41.450 --> 01:09:44.970
ERIC WEINER: You saved
the big question for last.

01:09:44.970 --> 01:09:47.424
VINT CERF: You're welcome.

01:09:47.424 --> 01:09:48.810
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:09:48.810 --> 01:09:51.143
ERIC WEINER: I think if you
read the book, first of all,

01:09:51.143 --> 01:09:53.351
you'll be surprised
at how much fun it is.

01:09:53.351 --> 01:09:54.350
Because it is a journey.

01:09:57.390 --> 01:10:00.020
And the question, though,
that I wrestled with,

01:10:00.020 --> 01:10:03.740
is, I know people like to have
everything tied up in a bow.

01:10:03.740 --> 01:10:06.750
And they like to know
what the formula is.

01:10:06.750 --> 01:10:09.120
And I wrestle with
that, because the book

01:10:09.120 --> 01:10:11.670
is very much an intellectual
journey, and an exploration.

01:10:11.670 --> 01:10:14.150
Trying to really, in a
really open minded way,

01:10:14.150 --> 01:10:16.640
figure out what the
heck was going on there,

01:10:16.640 --> 01:10:18.880
and what can we learn from it?

01:10:18.880 --> 01:10:23.840
And in the epilogue, I do
come up with a small bow.

01:10:23.840 --> 01:10:26.860
What I call the three
D's, which I think

01:10:26.860 --> 01:10:29.850
are essential to
all of these places.

01:10:29.850 --> 01:10:32.680
And I thought of a fourth
D since the book came out,

01:10:32.680 --> 01:10:37.050
but that's OK, it's in there
anyway, in other forms.

01:10:37.050 --> 01:10:40.727
And that is diversity,
discernment, and disorder.

01:10:40.727 --> 01:10:41.810
We've talked a bit about--

01:10:41.810 --> 01:10:42.685
VINT CERF: Diversity?

01:10:42.685 --> 01:10:45.540
ERIC WEINER: Diversity,
discernment, and disorder.

01:10:45.540 --> 01:10:47.314
VINT CERF: Discernment
and disorder.

01:10:47.314 --> 01:10:48.855
ERIC WEINER: Add a
little discomfort.

01:10:51.592 --> 01:10:52.550
Let's make it four D's.

01:10:52.550 --> 01:10:53.345
What the heck?

01:10:53.345 --> 01:10:54.900
VINT CERF: What's
the fourth one?

01:10:54.900 --> 01:10:55.690
ERIC WEINER: Discomfort.

01:10:55.690 --> 01:10:56.460
VINT CERF: Oh, discomfort.

01:10:56.460 --> 01:10:57.060
Oh good.

01:10:57.060 --> 01:10:57.671
Yes.

01:10:57.671 --> 01:10:58.170
Yay.

01:10:58.170 --> 01:10:59.378
ERIC WEINER: Yay, discomfort.

01:10:59.378 --> 01:11:02.059
And so they all
have this in common,

01:11:02.059 --> 01:11:03.850
but then they all have
their unique flavors

01:11:03.850 --> 01:11:05.470
and other things going on.

01:11:05.470 --> 01:11:08.500
Diversity, I'm not
really speaking

01:11:08.500 --> 01:11:10.930
about ethnic diversity,
though that does help.

01:11:10.930 --> 01:11:13.670
I'm speaking about
intellectual diversity.

01:11:13.670 --> 01:11:15.440
But typically people
from other places

01:11:15.440 --> 01:11:17.750
tend to bring other
ideas, which is helpful.

01:11:17.750 --> 01:11:21.730
A free flow of ideas.

01:11:21.730 --> 01:11:23.050
That kind of diversity.

01:11:23.050 --> 01:11:25.910
And really, it doesn't
begin with the letter D

01:11:25.910 --> 01:11:28.470
because it's a letter O, but
it's important, too openness.

01:11:28.470 --> 01:11:30.090
Openness to experience.

01:11:30.090 --> 01:11:32.460
That's the one trait
that psychologists

01:11:32.460 --> 01:11:34.760
say is the most important
for creative people,

01:11:34.760 --> 01:11:36.610
and I would say creative places.

01:11:36.610 --> 01:11:38.590
It's pretty broad, I
know, but it's important.

01:11:38.590 --> 01:11:40.540
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:11:40.540 --> 01:11:42.600
Number two is
discernment, because it's

01:11:42.600 --> 01:11:44.760
like the flip side
of the openness.

01:11:44.760 --> 01:11:46.550
You can't just have tolerance.

01:11:46.550 --> 01:11:49.824
Las Vegas is a pretty darn
tolerant place, but not

01:11:49.824 --> 01:11:52.365
a lot of genius coming out of
there, except for Andre Agassi.

01:11:56.920 --> 01:12:01.880
Jonas Salk, two-time
Nobel prize winner,

01:12:01.880 --> 01:12:04.950
once asked by a young
student, Dr. Salk,

01:12:04.950 --> 01:12:07.050
how do you come up with
so many good ideas?

01:12:07.050 --> 01:12:08.780
He said, well it's easy.

01:12:08.780 --> 01:12:12.670
I come up with lots of ideas,
and I throw out the bad ones.

01:12:12.670 --> 01:12:14.000
That's discernment.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:14.692
It's important.

01:12:14.692 --> 01:12:16.650
So these places of genius
are not only magnets,

01:12:16.650 --> 01:12:18.110
they're colanders.

01:12:18.110 --> 01:12:19.540
And the third is disorder.

01:12:19.540 --> 01:12:21.530
This is the chaos
we talked about.

01:12:21.530 --> 01:12:23.430
The low level of tension.

01:12:23.430 --> 01:12:26.790
Not war, but tension.

01:12:26.790 --> 01:12:29.420
A stirring of the pot.

01:12:29.420 --> 01:12:32.820
May you live in interesting
times, as the Chinese say.

01:12:32.820 --> 01:12:36.510
That applies well for
creative places as well.

01:12:36.510 --> 01:12:40.530
And then discomfort, which
we're adding here right now,

01:12:40.530 --> 01:12:44.570
because this speaks to the need
for constraints and challenges,

01:12:44.570 --> 01:12:47.110
and to have something
to push against.

01:12:47.110 --> 01:12:50.924
And to just bring Google in
briefly, if I can do that?

01:12:50.924 --> 01:12:51.590
VINT CERF: Sure.

01:12:51.590 --> 01:12:53.070
ERIC WEINER: OK.

01:12:53.070 --> 01:12:55.920
I'll be honest, one
thing that concerns

01:12:55.920 --> 01:13:00.330
me, but I think that Google
is doing well, is you

01:13:00.330 --> 01:13:01.600
want to attract talent.

01:13:01.600 --> 01:13:04.000
You want to bring in the
best and the brightest.

01:13:04.000 --> 01:13:10.430
But I think you don't want to
make people too comfortable.

01:13:10.430 --> 01:13:13.382
You want them to be challenged.

01:13:13.382 --> 01:13:15.340
VINT CERF: Do you want
to know how we did that?

01:13:15.340 --> 01:13:16.048
ERIC WEINER: How?

01:13:16.048 --> 01:13:19.090
VINT CERF: Well, you know how
we have these little mini cafe,

01:13:19.090 --> 01:13:20.450
micro kitchens everywhere?

01:13:20.450 --> 01:13:22.250
When I came to
Google, 10 years ago,

01:13:22.250 --> 01:13:23.580
it was junk food everywhere.

01:13:23.580 --> 01:13:25.710
We were in heaven.

01:13:25.710 --> 01:13:28.207
And then the junk food police
came along, and they said,

01:13:28.207 --> 01:13:29.290
you know what we're doing?

01:13:29.290 --> 01:13:31.760
We're destroying the health
of our best engineers.

01:13:31.760 --> 01:13:33.520
And so they took all
the junk food away,

01:13:33.520 --> 01:13:35.850
and there was this small
eruption after that.

01:13:35.850 --> 01:13:39.090
And the compromise was that
the good food is at eye level,

01:13:39.090 --> 01:13:40.686
and the not so good
food is down here,

01:13:40.686 --> 01:13:42.310
and the really junk
food is down there,

01:13:42.310 --> 01:13:44.300
and you have to
squat down to get it,

01:13:44.300 --> 01:13:46.090
and it's obvious when
you're doing that,

01:13:46.090 --> 01:13:48.380
and you get a little
exercise in the process.

01:13:48.380 --> 01:13:50.990
So that's how we managed to
generate a certain amount

01:13:50.990 --> 01:13:53.230
of creative discomfort.

01:13:53.230 --> 01:13:57.950
ERIC WEINER: A little
discomfort is good.

01:13:57.950 --> 01:14:01.220
Keep the constraints in there.

01:14:01.220 --> 01:14:04.870
You know, maybe people should
receive mild electric shocks

01:14:04.870 --> 01:14:08.820
randomly just to keep
them on their toes.

01:14:08.820 --> 01:14:10.709
So I think those are the key.

01:14:10.709 --> 01:14:12.500
I'd probably say, the
one thing is probably

01:14:12.500 --> 01:14:16.411
the openness to experience.

01:14:16.411 --> 01:14:18.160
You don't see a lot
of geniuses coming out

01:14:18.160 --> 01:14:20.600
of Pyongyang, North Korea.

01:14:20.600 --> 01:14:21.500
And why is that?

01:14:21.500 --> 01:14:23.090
This goes back to
my original thesis.

01:14:23.090 --> 01:14:25.420
Well, if you believe
that genius is genetic,

01:14:25.420 --> 01:14:27.920
then you have to say, well the
North Koreans have bad genes,

01:14:27.920 --> 01:14:28.730
well they don't.

01:14:28.730 --> 01:14:30.270
Their genetics are fine.

01:14:30.270 --> 01:14:32.160
Or if you believe it's
all about hard work,

01:14:32.160 --> 01:14:33.330
you would have to
say well, there

01:14:33.330 --> 01:14:35.204
are no geniuses because
they don't work hard,

01:14:35.204 --> 01:14:36.390
and they work plenty hard.

01:14:36.390 --> 01:14:37.515
VINT CERF: OK.

01:14:37.515 --> 01:14:39.140
ERIC WEINER: So what
are you left with?

01:14:39.140 --> 01:14:40.223
You're left with the soil.

01:14:40.223 --> 01:14:43.190
You're left with a
society that is not open.

01:14:43.190 --> 01:14:45.110
That's the opposite
of an open society.

01:14:45.110 --> 01:14:47.440
And I think that explains a lot.

01:14:47.440 --> 01:14:48.900
VINT CERF: It does indeed.

01:14:48.900 --> 01:14:52.820
Well let me ask all of us to
thank you for writing the book

01:14:52.820 --> 01:14:53.720
and joining us today.

01:14:53.720 --> 01:14:54.678
ERIC WEINER: Thank you.

01:14:54.678 --> 01:14:56.170
VINT CERF: Thank you.

